# Part 2: Relationships

### 1. AUTHOR – BOOK
Relationship Type: One-to-Many (1:N)  
FK Location: BOOK table (AuthorID as FK)

Explanation: One author can write many books, but each book has one author.

---

### 2. CITIZEN – PASSPORT
Relationship Type: One-to-One (1:1)  
FK Location: PASSPORT table (CitizenID as FK)

Explanation: One citizen has one passport, and each passport belongs to one citizen.

---

### 3. CUSTOMER – ORDER
Relationship Type: One-to-Many (1:N)  
FK Location: ORDER table (CustomerID as FK)

Explanation: One customer can place many orders, but each order belongs to one customer.

---

### 4. STUDENT – CLASS
Relationship Type: Many-to-Many (N:N)  
FK Location: Junction table (STUDENT_CLASS)

STUDENT_CLASS table:
StudentID (FK)  
ClassID (FK)

Explanation: A student can join many classes and a class can have many students.

---

### 5. TEAM – PLAYER
Relationship Type: One-to-Many (1:N)  
FK Location: PLAYER table (TeamID as FK)

Explanation: One team has many players, but each player belongs to one team.
